7 Endangered Languages and Where They Are

This is the map of the 7 chosen endangered languages: Jejueo, Tombonuo, Nyang'i, Hawaiʻi Sign Language, Taushiro, Pite Sámi and Yinhawangka. Click on a red pinpoint to see more information about each language!

Tombonuo

Alternative names: Tombonuwo, Tambanuo, Sungai, Lobu
Location & primary spoken areas: Sabah (Malaysia)
Roughly how many speakers left: Estimated under 10,000
Structurally similar languages: Linkabau (Tombonuo is a Paitanic language)
Unique linguistic features: The only marked tense (adding affixes like -ed in English) in Tombonuo is the simple past, and it also uses “focus” morphology, which differentiates the different relationships between subjects/objects and verbs, depending on the affix added to the word.

Jejueo

Alternative names: 제줏말, Jeju, Jejuan, Jejumal
Location & primary spoken areas: Jeju-do (South Korea), Ikuno-ku (Japan)
Roughly how many speakers left: Estimated under 1000
Structurally similar languages: Korean, Middle Korean (Jejueo is a Koreanic language)
Unique linguistic features: The Jejueo alphabet contains an extra vowel /ɒ/ (arae-a/아래아, symbolised by a dot) that is considered archaic in the modern Korean language and is no longer used, and also uses different vowels and consonants from Korean.

Yinhawangka

Alternative names: Inawangga, Inawongga, Ngaunmardi, Nalawonga
Location & primary spoken areas: Pilbara (Australia)
Roughly how many speakers left: Estimated 3
Structurally similar languages: Banyjima (Yinhawangka is a Ngayarda language)
Unique linguistic features: Some Pilbara languages (this includes Yinhawangka) are agglutinative, which means that multiple suffixes can be added onto a root word, to convey multiple meanings, and Yinhawangka also has a free word order, as the subject/object is marked with a suffix rather than being shown by the word order.

Hawaiʻi Sign Language

Alternative names: HSL (abbrv), Hawaiʻi Pidgin Sign Language, Hōʻailona ʻŌlelo o Hawaiʻi
Location & primary spoken areas: Hawaiʻi
Roughly how many speakers left: Estimated 30
Structurally similar languages: HSL is a unique language that is largely unrelated to any other sign languages, though there also exists a Creole Hawaiʻi Sign Language which is a creole (mix) of HSL and ASL (HSL is a sign language)
Unique linguistic features: Whereas many other sign languages use the adjective-noun grammatical format, HSL puts the noun before the adjective (which is also true for the Hawaiian language), and also uses a larger “signing space”, where signs can occur not only with the hands, but also other body parts.

Taushiro

Alternative names: Pinche, Pinchi
Location & primary spoken areas: Peruvian Amazon
Roughly how many speakers left: 1 (Amadeo García García)
Structurally similar languages: There are no demonstrable genealogical relationships to any other known languages (Taushiro is a language isolate)
Unique linguistic features: The Taushiro numbering system only goes up to 10 (likely due to the fact that the tribe does not need elaborate systems and just requires efficient communication), and any numbers higher than 10 would just be referred to as “ashintu”, meaning many.

Pite Sámi

Alternative names: Arjeplog Saami, Pitesamisk, Pitesamiska, Piitimensaame
Location & primary spoken areas: Arjeplog (Sweden)
Roughly how many speakers left: Estimated under 30
Structurally similar languages: Lule Sámi, Ume Sámi, Southern Sámi (Pite Sámi is a Sámi language)
Unique linguistic features: Pite Sámi has a quite unique vocabulary and prosodic characteristics that are unlike most Indo-European languages, but also uses consonant gradation, which is where consonants may change in a word based on whether they are “strong” or “weak” (this is not in the typical sense, but rather whether the word ends with a vowel or consonant respectively/whether the consonants are voiced or voiceless plosives).

Nyang'i

Alternative names: Nuangeya, Nyuangia, Nyangiya
Location & primary spoken areas: Northeastern Uganda
Roughly how many speakers left: Estimated under 8
Structurally similar languages: Karamojong, Soo (Nyang’i is a Kuliak language)
Unique linguistic features: As there is only one fluent speaker of Nyang’i left (Komol Isaach, while the others have other dominant languages) and the language is underdocumented, the documentations that we have now reflect on his personal mannerisms of speech, making them more like documentations of an idiolect, which are the speech habits of a particular person.

These are 7 endangered languages, most of which are critically endangered. Unfortunately, I could not include more, as it is estimated that around 3,200 of the 7,100 languages in the world are endangered, and there are many that are on the brink of extinction. If you would like to learn more, you can find more information in the "More Information" tab at the top.
